<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>CHALLENGE TO INSIDER TRADING RULING FAILS</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> On Friday, the United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit denied Preet Bhararaâs request to reconsider a decision in December that sharply narrowed the definition of insider trading. Now left with few legal options, the United States attorney for Manhattan may need to rely on Congress to protect the legacy of his crackdown on insider trading, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/04/business/dealbook/appeals-court-rejects-request-to-rehear-landmark-insider-trading-case.html?_r=0">Matthew Goldstein and Ben Protess write in DealBook. </a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Because no federal law defines insider trading, it has been left to federal judges and regulators to determine what it means to trade on confidential tips. In December, a three-judge panel of the Court of Appeals <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/12/10/appeals-court-overturns-2-insider-trading-convictions/"> dismissed insider trading charges</a> against the former hedge fund traders Anthony Chiasson and Todd Newman, ruling that the two men needed to know that insiders at technology companies were improperly leaking confidential information in exchange for some <b> âpersonal benefit.â</b> The judges also ruled that the government had to show that the tipper expected to receive something <b>âof some consequenceâ</b> in return.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> The ruling was not clear on what constitutes âsome consequence,â which worries federal prosecutors. In its request for a reconsideration of the panelâs decision, Mr. Bhararaâs office said the âerroneous definition of the personal benefit requirement will <b>dramatically limit the governmentâs ability to prosecute</b> some of the most common culpable and market-threatening forms of insider trading.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> In the wake of the December ruling, lawmakers in Washington have  <b>introduced at least three bills</b> that would establish clearer ground rules for insider trading prosecutions, which could help stem the fallout from the ruling. One of them, introduced by Senator Jack Reed, Democrat of Rhode Island, would eliminate the need to prove a personal benefit, simply defining unlawful insider trading as a trade that is made on material information that a person has reason to know is confidential.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Ira Lee Sorkin, a white-collar defense lawyer, said the appeals court decision on Friday might increase the pressure on Congress to clarify insider trading. However, given the gridlock in Washington, âthe idea of passing any insider trading law in Congress might be wishful thinking,â write Mr. Goldstein and Mr. Protess.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>DISPARITY IN RECOVERIES FOR WRONGED INVESTORS</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> An analysis of financial crisis lawsuits cited most recently on the Securities and Exchange Commissionâs website shows that 23 of them generated nearly $2.6 billion for investors who lost money because of improprieties by individuals and financial institutions, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/05/business/victims-of-financial-wrongdoing-need-a-more-muscular-sec.html">Gretchen Morgenson writes in the Fair Game column.</a> But that amount pales in comparison to the recoveries generated by law firms that brought class-action lawsuits on behalf of stockholders and debtholders.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> In six cases in which the same financial institutions were sued on the same facts by both the S.E.C. and private plaintiffs, the S.E.C. recovered $400 million for investors while the private plaintiffs received almost $3.8 billion, net of legal fees and expenses. The vast difference between the amounts reflects the <b>limits placed on the S.E.C. under the law,</b> which forbids the agency from seeking a penalty that exceeds the financial gain a wrongdoer made, even if losses incurred by investors as a result of the improprieties are far greater. âThe disparity in recoveries is telling,â writes Ms. Morgenson. âIt shows, among other things, how crucial it is for investors to be able to bring private actions under the securities laws.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Andrew J. Ceresney, the agencyâs director of enforcement, said that the S.E.C. has asked Congress for the authority to increase the amount the agency can extract in penalties but that it has not been granted. âThe agency is clearly hamstrung in its efforts to generate recoveries on behalf of harmed investors,â writes Ms. Morgenson. âIsnât it time to ensure that when the S.E.C. comes knocking, the fine fits the crime?â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>ON THE AGENDA</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The <b>Markit services purchasing managersâ index for March</b> comes out at 9:45 a.m. The <b>ISM nonmanufacturing index</b> will be released at 10 a.m. <b>William C. Dudley,</b> president of the New York Fed, will discuss the economy in a speech at 8:30 a.m. in Newark, N.J. </p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>GREECE MEETS WITH I.M.F. OVER DEBT PAYMENT</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The Greek finance minister, Yanis Varoufakis, met with the International Monetary Fundâs managing director, Christine Lagarde, in Washington on Sunday as the due date neared for a 458 million euro, or $503 million, payment to the fund, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/06/business/international/greece-and-imf-hold-talks-on-crucial-debt-payment.html">Landon Thomas Jr. writes in The New York Times.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> After the meeting, Ms. Lagarde said she welcomed âconfirmation by the minister that payment owing to the fund would be forthcoming on April 9th,â the deadline for Greeceâs debt payment. Mr. Varoufakis said that Greece would meet all its obligations, âalthough <b>neither party provided details</b> in terms of how Greece would secure the funds to make this happen,â writes Mr. Thomas.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Mr. Varoufakis is also planning to meet with officials in the United States Treasury on Monday in the hope that the United States, as the dominant voice at the I.M.F., might pressure fund officials, and Europe as well, to cut Greece some slack. Also, Prime Minister Alexis Tsipras of Greece is scheduled to meet with <b>President Vladimir V. Putin of Russia</b> in Moscow this week, increasing speculation that Greece is looking for another source of funds.</p>
</div>
